OUR DRIVER WAS AT THE G.E. PLANT TO LOAD.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO REMAIN IN THE CAB OF THE TRACTOR.  THE G.E. LOADER (LEROY) WAS LOADING TANK #564. HE WAS UNAWRE THAT SOMEONE HAD OPENED A SECOND VALVE, AND WHEN THE TANK BECAME FULL, HE SHUT DOWN HIS VALVE.  HOWEVER, WITH THE SECOND VALVE BEING, OPEN, APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OVER THE SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK BEFOE HE (LEROY) COULD SHUT IT DOWN.  THEY INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO REMAIN IN THE TRACTOR AND THEY CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  THIS WAS ALL WITHIN THEIR PLANT.

column168: PROPANE TANKER TRAVELING SOUTH ON CITY RD 36, SNOW PLOW, CAR AND PICKUP TRAVELING NORTH.  AS THE 4 VECHICLES CONVERGED THE SNOW PLOW HIT A DRIFT. A WHITE OUT OCCURRED.  THE PROPANE TANKER AND THE CAR COLLIDED IN THE WHITE OUT.  THE IMPACT PUSHED THE TRUCK BUMPER INTO THE LEFT FRONT WHEEL, THE DRIVER COULD NOT STEER AND WENT INTO THE DITCH AND A ARTERY ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE ROAD.  WE THEORIZE THE RELIEF VALVES RELEASED A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR ON IMPACT THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF ANY LIQUID WHEN THE TANK CAME TO REST.  THE PROPANE WAS BUMPED OFF THE TRANSPORT INTO ANOTHER TANKER AND DELIVERED TO THE MAGMESSON FARM.  WE RECOVERED 100 % OF THE PRODUCT THAT WAS INTO THE TANKER AND DELIVERED OUR 9300 GALLONS OF PROPANE TO THE FARM TANK.

REPAIRED LIQUID AMMONIA BALL VALVES LEAKED THROUGH DURING LOADING OF RAILCAR.  WHEN DISCOVERED, LOADING WAS STOPPED.  THE RAILCAR WAS DEPRESSURED AND SENT TO THE SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  OUR RECOMMENDATION IS TO HAVE BALL VALVES TESTED IN THE REPAIR SHOP WITH HANDLES IN PLACE TO ASSURE THAT BALL VALVE SEATS OFF WITH HANDLES ATTACHED.  BALL VALVES HAVE A TENDENCY NOT TO SEAT PROPERLY UNLESS THE VALVE HANDLES AND VALVE HANDLE STOP ARE MANUFACTURED WITH EXTREMELY CLOSE TOLERANCE.  DOT SHOULD POSSIBLE LOOK INTO THE RELIABLITY OF BALL VALVE USE IN AMMONIA RAILCAR SERVICE.

ALSO THERE SHOULD BE MORE PACKAGING MATERIALS INSIDE THE BOXES WHEN THERE CONTAINES GLASS JUGS TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN. column168: ON 2-11-94 A VAN WATERS & ROGERS DRIVER WAS PUMPING METHANE FROM HIS PULL TRAILER ON HIS TRUCK TANK, (IN AN ATTEMPT TO EQUALIZE THE WEIGHT OF THE UNIT) WHILE DOING SO HE OVERFILLED THE TRUCK TANK SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 50 TO 75 GALLONS OF VIRGIN METHOD (UN1230) THREE VAN WATERS & ROGERS EMPLOYEES (INCLUDING MYSELF) WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL (ALL OF WHOM CARRY HAZWOPER CERTIFICATION) THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING SCOOP SHOVELS & SQEEGEES (THE ETHANOL WAS MIXED WITH SNOW & PRETTY WELL DILUTED AT THIS POINT) THE GROUND WAS FROZEN IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL AND PREVENTED THE METHANOL FROM PENETRATING THE SOIL, V W & R PERSONNEL CLEANED ALL OF THE SURROUNDING AREA AND ALSO THE SPILL SIGHT TO THE POINT THAT THERE WAS NOTHING LEFT BUT FROZEN SOIL THE WASTE WAS PLACED INTO 3 80 GALLONS RECOVERY DRUM AND IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD FOR PROPER IDENTIFICATION AND DISPOSAL.

HE THEN NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE SEALED CONTAINER AND NOTIFIED THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL ON DUTY AT THE SCALE FACILITY. WHEN CONTAINER WAS OPENED IT WAS FOUND THAT THE POLYURETHANE DRUMS HAD BEEN PACKED AND STRAPPED ONTO PALLETS.  DURING TRANSPORTATION LOAD HAD SHIFTED CAUSING IT TO BE OVERWEIGHT ON AXLE AT LIVERMORE SCALE.  IT APPEARS THAT THIS SHIFTING CAUSED THE DRUM TO BE PUNCTURED BY A NAIL IN A PALLET.  THE PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE CONTAINER FLOOR AND EVENTUALLY OUT OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE DIRT.  EXPRESS INTERMODAL TRANSPORT DID NOT SEE THE CONTENTS OR THE LOADING UNTIL THE DOORS WERE OPENED BY THE DISPOSAL CREW.

column168: THE DRIVER NOTIFED THE N & M SAFETY OFFICE OF A SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 A.M. ON 2/23/93.  HE FIRST BECAME AWARE OF THE SPILL WHEN THE RUPTURED MATERIAL BEGAN LEAKING ON THE FLOOR IN TO THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. THE DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING WAS IN THE VERY NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  AFTER NOTICING THE SPILL, THE FIRST ACTION N & M TRANSFER DRIVER TOOK WAS TO TIP THE PUNCTURED DRUM ON ITS SIDE.  THIS ACTION STOPPED THE FLOW OF LEAKING MATERIAL.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO THE CAB OF HIS TRACTOR WHERE HE PULLED OUT OIL DRY.  HE SPREAD THE OIL DRY THROUGHOUT THE TRAILER AND ALSO USED A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF IT TO DIKE LAST QUARTER OF HIS TRAILER.  THE SHIPMENT THAT CONTAINED THIS LEAKING DRUM WAS TRANSFERRED AND LOADED ON TO THIS TRAILER JUST AS IT WAS PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER.  (THIS SHIPMENT WAS SHRINK WRAPPED ON A SKID.) BECAUSE THE SHIPPER DID NOT PROPERLY EXAMINE THEIR SKIDS BEFORE LOADING, THEY FAILED TO SEE A PORTRUDING NAIL WHICH CAUSED THE PUNCTURE AND THE LEAKAGE.  COMMENT:  PUNCTURING THE BOTTOMS OF POLYETHYLENE DRUMS WITH NAILS OCCURS MORE THAN IT SHOULD. CONTAINER MANUFACTURERS SHOULD BE REQUIRED TO REINFORCE THE BOTTOMS OF ALL POLYETHYLENE DRUMS.

column168: VANCE COLE WAS LOADING AUS OFF THE DOCK.  HE LOADED THE PALLET WITH THIS FREIGHT ON IT, AND THEN LOADED ANOTHER PALLET BEHIND IT, AND HIS BLADES PUNCTURED THIS CAN.  HE WENT TO LOAD OTHER FREIGHT AND WHEN IT WAS NOTICED LEAKING, IT HAD DONE ALL LEAKED OUT OF THE 5 GALLON CAN.  BY THE TIME WE HAD GOTTEN BACK WITH OUR SPILL KIT, THE NAPTHA HAD DONE ALL EVAPORATED. WE MUST KEEP TELLING OUR PEOPLE TO USE CAUTION ON FORKLIFTS.

column168: DUMP TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH CONTAMINATED SOIL AT AUGUSTA, GA DURING A RAIN STORM.  WHILE LOAD WAS BEING REMANIFESTED IN REIDSVILLE, NC IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT WATER WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE TAILGATE.  APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON OF LIQUIDS LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER.  THIS LIQUID WAS CONTAINED IN A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL BY LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL.  ADDITIONAL WATER WAS DRAINED FROM THE TRAILER AND THE LOAD WAS STABILIZED USING PORTLAND CEMENT AND OIL DRY.  THE LOAD WAS THEN REMANIFESTED AND SENT TO ENVOTECH IN BELLEVILLE, MI FOR FINAL DISPOSAL.  TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE LEAKS CARRIER WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT TAILGATE SEALS AND LATCHES AS PART OF MONTHLY ROUTINE MAINTENANCE PROCEDURE.  AS ADDITIONAL PRECAUTION SILICONE OR COMPARABLE SEALANT WILL BE USED TO SEAL GRAIN DOORS AND TAILGATES WHEN POTENTIALLY WET LOADS ARE ENCOUNTERED.  DRIVERS WILL ALSO BE TRAINED TO RECOGNIZE POTENTIAL PROBLEM LOADS AND WILL BE INSTRUCED TO NOTIFY DISPATCH BEFORE LOADING.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM VALENTINE PLATING COMPANY, INC. LOCATED AT 155 ALLSTON AVENUE IN WEST SPRINGFIELD, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC. LOCATED IN NATICK, MA IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM CONTAINER ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VECHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL INTO A NEW CUBIC YARD FIBER BOX.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE NEW CONTAINER AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT DURING TRANSPORTATION, RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED, SEPARATED FROM THE MATERIAL AND DEGRADED THE SIDE WALL AND BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL MATERIAL LOADED INTO THIS TYPE OF CONTAINER IS FREE OF ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT COULD ADVERSELY AFFECT THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF THE CONTAINER.

A VAN TAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM BADGER STATE REPAIR LOCATED AT 204 WEST CENTRALIA STREET IN ELKHORN, WI TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF NATICK, INC. LOCATED IN NATICK, MA IT WAS DISCOVERD THAT APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM AND SIDE SEAM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DRUMS FROZE ENROUTE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION CAUSING THE BOTTOM AND SIDE SEAM TO FAIL.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND. IN ADDITION, CONTAINERS WILL BE MONITORED DURING EXTREME WEATHER CONDITIONS IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY POTENTIAL DRUM FAILURES.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: I ENTERED THE UNLOADING AREA (NORTH) FROM THE RAILROAD TRACK SIDE OF THE AREA TO WHERE THE PRODUCT WAS TO BE DELIVERED.  SEE MY DRAWING (NOT TO SCALE) OF THE SITE AND APPROACH ROAD AREA. I STEERED TO THE RIGHT AS MUCH AS I THOUGHT I COULD (THERE WAS SOME LUMBERYARD MATERIALS TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE DRIVEWAY APPROACH TO THE UNLOADING AREA).  CLEAR ICE WAS ABUNDANT IN THE AREA.  WHEN I STARTED MY LEFT TURN (WEST), AS I BEEN INSTRUCTED, TO HAVE THE TRACTOR AS CLOSE TO THE UNLOADING DOCK AS POSSIBLE.  WHEN I GOT TO POINT 1, THERE WAS ICE UNDER THE TRACTOR STEERING AXLE AND TRACTOR DRIVE WHEELS, WHEREBY I COULDN'T GET THE TRACOTR TO TURN LEFT.  I BACKED UP TWO OR THREE TIMES, POSSIBLE MORE, BEFORE THE DRIVE WHEELS AND FRONT AXLE OBTAINED THE TRACTION TO MOVE FORWARD AGAIN.  NOW I HAD THE TRACTOR NEARLY PARALLEL WITH THE LOADING DOCK.  BY THIS TIME THE TRAILER AXLES WERE ALSO ON ICE. MY FAILURE TO SPLIT MY ATTENTION TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR.  WHEN I HEARD A SQUEALING NOISE, I CHECKED MY LEFT MIRROR.  PLEASE UNDERSTAND THAT THE LIGHTING, LIGHT REFLECTIONS, SOLIED MIRRORS AND WINDOWS WERE ALSO CONTRIBUTING FACTORS.  I STOPPED AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE AFTER HEARING THE SQUEALING NOISE.  I TRIED, MOMENTARILY, TO BACK UP, BUT I CAN'T HELP THINKING...THAT AT THAT MOMENT OR DURING THOSE MONEMTS THE TRAILER HAD TO HAVE ALSO SLID TO THE LEFT, CAUSING THE TANK TO RUPTURE.  WITH THE STEEL "I" BEAM FIRMLY IN PLACE AND GASOLINE FLOWING FROM THE POINT OF RUPTURE, I SHUT OFF THE ENGINE, EXITED THE CAB, RAN TO THE SIMONSOM STORE, AND DIRECTED A PERSON WORKING IN THE STORE TO CALL 911, AND AKSED FOR FIRE FIGHTERS TO RESPOND TO A GASOLINE SPILL AT THAT LOCATION.  I WENT BACK TO THE ACCIDENT SITE TO WATCH THE AREA AND WAIT FOR THE FARGO FIRE DEPARTMENT. I WOULD GUESS THE FIRST RESPONDERS ARRIVE IN 5 TO 10 MINNUTES.  THE PERSON I ASK TO CALL 911 WAS MR. LEWIS KLEIN, THE SIMONSON SERVICE STATION MANAGER.

column168: THE APPROPRIATE LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED, ALL OF WHICH SUPPORTED CWM'S ACTIONS.  THERE WAS NO MEDIA COVERAGE.  FROM INVESTIGATION AND INTERVIEWS WITH THE STATE AND COUNTY POLICE, AS WELL AS THE WRECKER SERVICE, WHITE-OUT CONDITIONS WITH HIGH WINDS EXISTED IN THIS AREA OF U.S. 30, WHILE OTHER AREAS WERE CLEAR WITH LIGHT SNOW.  THE DRIVER SIMPLY LOST SIGHT OF THE ROAD TRAVELING AT 5-10 MPH, NEAR A CURVE TO THE RIGHT, AND PROCEEDING STRAIGHT CROSSING THE MEDIAN, AND WEST BOUND LANES, AND WENT INTO AN EASEMENT DITCH.  THE RATE OF TRAVEL (5-10 MPH) APPEARS TO BE SUBSTANTIATED BECAUSE OF THE +35 DEGREE DECLINE INTO THE DITCH WHICH THE UNIT TRAVELLED WHERE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO TURN THE VEHICLE RIGHT, APPEARING TO PARALLEL PARK IN THE RAVINE, WITH NO DAMAGE SUSTAINED BY THE TRACTOR AND MINIMAL TO THE TRAILER, A DIRECT RESULT OF THE R/O BOX SLIDING OFF. THE DRIVER, UNDER THE CONDITIONS, WAS NOT ONLY VERY FORTUNATE, BUT DISPLAYED CORRECTIVE DRIVING SKILLS BY KEEPING THE UNIT UPRIGHT, MINIMIZING DAMAGE SUBSTANTIALLY.

DURING TRANSIT A LID ON A BOTTLE CONTAINING XYLENE HAD WORKED LOOSE.  SOME PRODUCT WAS LOST AND ABSORBED BY THE CARTON.  THE CAP WAS RESEALED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

DELMARVA OIL FUEL DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS PROCEEDING SOUTH ON US 13 IN WESTOVER, MD AND WHILE TRAVELING BEHIND A TRACTOR TRAILER, A CAR YIELDING FROM LAYFIELD RD CROSSED OVER INTO THE LEFT HAND PASSING LANE INTO THE PATH OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER, THEREFORE CAUSING THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO JACKNIFE AND THE DELMARVA OIL DELIVERY VEHICLE TO REAR END THE TRACTOR TRAILER.  AT THIS TIME, THE FUEL TANK COMPARTMENT RUPTURED CAUSING A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  THE DELMARVA OIL DELIVERY VEHICLE RESULTED IN A TOTAL LOSS DUE TO THIS INCIDENT.  THE DRIVER OF THE DMO DELIVERY VEHICLE RECEIVED A LACERATION ON HIS LEG AND BRUISES TO VARIOUS PARTS OF HIS BODY.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS NOT INJURED.  THE DRIVER OF THE IN FAULT VEHICLE RECEIVED CUTS AND BRUISES.  THE DMO DRIVER AND THE DRIVER OF THE IN FAULT VEHICLE WERE BOTH TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED.

DRIVER WAS GIVEN THE OKAY TO UNLOAD AFTER WAITING FOR CONSIGNEE TO MAKE ROOM IN STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER WAS THEN INSTRUCTED TO MAKE CONNECTION AND START TO AIR OFF CARGO TANK.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES OF UNLOADING, PRODUCT RELEASED OUT OF THE OVERFLOW/VAPOR RECOVERY LINE.  DRIVER SHUT OFF AIR SOURCE, DISCHARGE VALVE ON CARGO TANK, ALERTED PERSONNEL AND EVACUATED AREA.  CONSIGNEE ALERTED THEIR FIRE DEPT. AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP CONTAINATED AREA.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AT BASE OF TANK.  BALANCE OF LOAD WAS UNLOADED THE NEXT DAY.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED INCIDENT #221777.  CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED THE STATE AND LOCAL AGENCY.

ON FEBRUARY 28, 1994, A BURLINGTON NORTHERN TRACK INSPECTOR OBSERVED THAT THERE HAD BEEN AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY WHILE TRANSFERRING PHOSPHORIC ACID FROM TANK CAR GATX 41092 INTO TANK TRUCKS. THE CONSIGNEE WAS INSTRUCTED TO PROPERLY CLEAN UP AND NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS SUBSEQUENTLY OBSERVED BY A FEDERAL RAILROAD INSPECTOR FROM MOBILE, ALABAMA.

AFTER MAKING SETOUT AND DOING STATION SWITCHING, CREW WAS SHOVING 36 CARS WITH 4 LOCOMOTIVES TO RECOUPLE TRAIN.  DUE TO AN APPARENT AUDIO FAILURE, SPEED RECORDER INDICATED THAT THE REAR PORTION OF TRAIN WAS STRUCK AT 10 MPH.  THE RESULTING IMPACT AND DERAILMENT CAUSED TANK CAR RCRX 1029, RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID, TO BUCKLE AT THE CENTER OF THE TANK.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON SUNDAY, FEBRUARY 27, 1994, AT ABOUT 6:10 AM ON THE WEST SIDE OF BURLINGTON, NORTH DAKOTA, AT RAILROAD MILEPOST 477.  CP RAIL SYSTEM (SOO LINE RAILROAD), FREIGHT TRAIN #580-24, WITH 58 CARS (50 WERE LOADED AND 8 EMPTIES), DERAILED 26 CARS. OF THE 26 CARS DERAILED, 10 CONTAINED SODIUM SULPHATE; 1 CONTAINED MAGNESIUM OXIDE; 5 CONTAINED LUMBER; 2 TANK CARS CONTAINED PROPANE, WHICH WERE INTACT; 1 TANK CAR PROX 99082, CONTAINED ISOBUTANE, WHICH WAS PUNCTURED DURING THE DERAILMENT AND FED A FIRE; AND 1 WAS AN EMPTY TANK CAR LAST CONTAINING TOULENE DIISOCYANATE, APPARENTLY HAD THE BOTTOM OUTLET AND SAFETY VALVES BROKEN OFF, AND MAY HAVE RELEASED SOME TOXIC FUMES DURING THE INITIAL STAGES OF THE FIRES; AND THE REST WERE EMPTY TANK CARS.  THE TRAIN DEPARTED FROM PORTAL, NORTH DAKOTA AND WAS EN-ROUTE TO CHICAGO, ILLINOIS AT THE TIME OF THE DERAILMENT.  IT HAD A THREE MAN CREW THAT WAS BASED OUT OF HARVEY, NORTH DAKOTA WHICH INCLUDED AN ENGINEER, CONDUCTOR AND BRAKEMAN.  AFTER LEAVING PORTAL THE TRAIN RECEIVED A VISUAL INSPECTION BY THE CREW OF A PASSING TRAIN AT FOXHOLM AND PASSED OVER AN ELECTRONIC DETECTION DEVICE FOUR MILES WEST OF THE DERAILMENT SITE.  THE DETECTOR REPORT THAT THE TRAIN WAS GOING 38 MPH AND THAT THERE WERE NO DEFECTS.  THE RAILROAD BROUGHT IN TWO FIRMS TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP.  HULCHER PROFESSIONAL SERVICES (EQUIPMENT FROM MINNEAPOLIS AND DES MOINES) TO PHYSICALLY MOVE AND PICK-UP THE DERIALED CARS AND OH MATERIALS, FROM OHIO TO TRANSFER THE LOADS.  LOCAL FIRE AND EMERGENCY CREWS RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY AND THE BURLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENTS WAS ULTIMATELY SUPPLEMENTED WITH HELP FROM 18 FIRE DEPARTMENTS FROM AS FAR AWAY AS 100 MILES.  NINE PEOPLE WERE REPORTED TO HAVE RECEIVED INJURIES, AND SEVEN OF THEM WERE TREATED AND RELEASED ON THE DAY OF THE DERAILMENT. A TRAILER HOME OCCUPIED BY THE ROCKY YALE FAMILY WAS LOCATED ABOUT 200 FEET JUST TO THE NORTH OF THE DERAILMENT.  THE FAMILY REPORTEDLY WAS AWAKENED BY THE SOUND OF THE DERAILMENT (FATHER, MOTHER AND TWO SONS). THE FATHER WENT OUT THE DOOR OPPOSITE THE DERAILMENT WHILE HIS SON (A 16 YEAR OLD BOY, WENT OUT THE DOOR FACING THE DERAILMENT.  APPARENTLY, JUST AFTER THE 16 YEAR OLD BOY WENT OUT, THE ISOBUTANE IGNITED AND HE WAS IN THE FACE OF THE FLAME.  THE 16 YEAR OLD WAS TAKEN TO TRINITY HOSPITAL, IN MINOT, ND. AND SHORTLY THEREAFTER AIRLIFTED TO ST. PAUL RAMSEY MEDIAL CENTER, IN ST. PAUL, MN, WITH CRITICAL BURNS (2ND & 3RD DEGREE BURNS TO OVER 60 PERCENT OF HIS BODY).  BASED ON REPORTS, AN ARM WAS AMPUTATED AS THE RESULT OF HIS BURNS.  HIS FATHER, WAS ALSO TAKEN TO TRINITY HOSPITAL, IN MINOT, ND. AND ON FEBRUARY 28, 1994, WAS RELEASED WITH SUPERFICIAL BURNS ABOUT HIS FACE AND HANDS.  APPROXIMATELY 1500 RESIDENTS WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR RESIDENTS AT ABOUT 6:15 AM, AND REMAINED OUT OF THEIR HOMES FOR APPROXIMATELY 23 HOURS.  THEY WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN AT 5:00 AM, FEBRUARY 28, 1994, WHEN THE THREAT OF ANY FURTHER EXPLOSIONS WHERE REMOVED.  FIRE CREWS MAINTAINED STREAMS OF WATER ON T

ON FEBRUARY 9, 1994 AT 12:15 PM A GATEWAY WESTERN TRAINMAN DISCOVERED GATX 99533, CAR OF ISOPROPYL ACETATE, ON TRACK #29 B- YARD IN EAST ST. LOUIS LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OF OUTLET. A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE CONSIGNEE, TRANS. CHEMICAL IN ST. LOUIS, MISSOURI AND THE CAR WAS MOVE TO THE GATEWAY WESTERN "OLD PIG RAMP" AS A PRECAUTION. TRANS CHEMICAL SENT FOUR TANKER TRUCKS FOR LOAD TRANSFER AND ON ARRIVAL ONE OF THE DRIVERS WENT TO THE DOME OF THE CAR AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. CAR WAS RELEASED TO FISCAL DESTINATION. ACCORDING TO THE CONSIGNEE, APPROXIMATELY 340 GALLONS OF THE COMMODITY LEAKED FROM THE CAR AND THAT CLEAN-UP WOULD NOT BE NECESSARY DUE TO THE RAPID EVAPORATION OF THE COMMODITY.

LOCATED IN CHICAGO, IL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM AND SIDE SEAM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS THEN DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY LISTED ON THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ENSECO, INCORPORATED LOCATED AT 2200 COTTONTAIL LANE IN SOMERSET, NJ TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA. DURING A ROUTINE STOP IN MAPLEWOOD, NJ, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICHLE DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SCENE, THE CLEAN-UP CREW IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING CONTAINER, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER ALONG WITH ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SALVAGE DRUM CONTAINING THE CLEAN-UP DEBRIS AND ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 P.M. ON FEBUARY 17, 1994, THE DRIVER OF A CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT TRUCK STOPPED ON ROUTE 50 (CICERO AVENUE) AT 87TH STREET. THE DRIVER WAS CARRYING A 20 YARD ROLL-OFF BOX ON A SEMI-TRAILER. HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO CONTROL A SMALL LEAK FROM A SLIT IN THE BACK OF THE ROLL-OFF BOX HE WAS CARRYING. THE BOX CONTAINED WASTE SULFUR, A NON-HAZARDOUS SPECIAL WASTE, WHICH HAD BEEN PICKED UP IN BEDFORD PARK, IL AND WAS DESTINED FOR A CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IN CALUMET CITY, IL. WHILE THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED, AN OFFICER FROM THE HOMETOWN, IL POLICE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED. THE HOMETOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS DESCRIBED AS A WHITE LIQUID. THE SLIT WAS APPARENTLY MADE BY A FORKLIFT AND WAS APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES BY 1/2 INCH. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT LESS THAN 5 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE BOX. THE TRUCK DRIVER STOPPED THE LEAK USING A SHOP TOWEL. FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE INCIDENT WAS MINOR AND THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE DANGER TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC OR THE ENVIRONMENT. THE HOMETOWN FIRE DEPARTMENT WATER-FLUSHED THE LEAKED MATERIAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 P.M. REPRESENTATIVES FROM CENTRAL WASTE MANAGEMENT ARRIVED, AND COVERED THE SLIT IN THE WALL OF THE ROLL-OFF, USING SHEET METAL. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 P.M. THE TRUCK AND THE LOAD WERE RELEASED TO THE CUSTODY OF THE DRIVER. CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT WAS CITED FOR VIOLATING SECTION 173.24(B) OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE. THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO CALUMET CITY, IL.

IT WAS RAINING ON THE NIGHT OF FEBRUARY 10, 1994 AND THE DRIVER PLANNED TO PULL INTO A PARKING LOT AT MIDNIGHT TO STOP FOR A BREAK.  HE ASKED A FELLOW TRUCKER BEHIND HIM IF HE WAS CLEAR OF THE DITCH ON EITHER SIDE OF THE DRIVEWAY.  IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE TRAILER WOULD MISS THE DITCH. HOWEVER, THE BACK RIGHT TIRES ON THE TRAILER WENT INTO THE DITCH AND THE DRIVER WAS THEN STUCK AND NOT ABLE TO PULL HIMSELF OUT.  AT 0005 FEBRUARY 11, 1994 THE DRIVER CALLED THE LOCAL POLICE IN EUPORA, MS WHO IN TURN CALLED A TOW TRUCK OPERATOR.  THE TOW TRUCK OPERATOR DECIDED TO PULL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OUT OF THE DITCH BACKWARDS.  THEY DID NOT HEAR THE WARNING THE DRIVER YELLED WHEN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER CAUGHT THE CURB. THE BELLY VALVE WAS CRUSHED AND THE TRAILER BEGAN TO LEAK AT THE SEAMS. THE DRIVER AND TWO TRUCK OPERATOR TRIED TO CONTAIN THE LEAK AS BEST AS POSSIBLE WITH BUCKETS.  THE M S DEQ WAS CALLED AND A REPRESENTATIVE WAS AT THE SCENE WITHIN HOURS.  A CLEAN UP COMPANY IN THE AREA WAS CALLED AND WHEN THEY GOT TO THE SITE THEY TOOK OVER THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH AND EXTENSIVE CLEANUP CONTINUED AT THE SITE.  THIS ACCIDENT MAY HAVE BEEN PREVENTED IF THE TOW TRUCK OPERATOR HAD NOT TRIED TO PULL THE TRUCK AND TRAILER OUT OF THE DITCH BACKWARDS. COPIES OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFESTS ARE ATTACHED.

column168: REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MTO LEHAN AT SETTEGAST YARD THAT THE CARMAN HAD FOUND THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  REEDER ARRIVED AND DISCOVERED THE LEAK COMING FROM UNDER THE SEALED PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. SEAL "GRIBBLE STAMP 235156" WAS REMOVED.  THE LEAK WAS AROUND THE PACKING GLAND ON THE LIQUID VALVE.  REEDER RELIEVED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THERE WAS NO ADJUSTMENT AVAILABLE ON THE VALVE.  SINCE THE CAR WAS DESTINED TO THE FAR NORTH WHERE TEMPERATURES WERE MUCH COLDER, REEDER ELECTED TO LET THE CAR CONTINUE.  THE HOUSING WAS RESEALED WITH "MP 17 169090." CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  THE LOWER TEMPERATURES IN THE NORTH SHOULD KEEP THE CAR FROM BUILDING PRESSURE AND LEAKING AGAIN.  THIS TRAIN WAS CALLED FOR 230PM.  REEDER ARRIVED AT 230PM TO BEGIN WORK.  THERE WAS A DELAY OF APPROXIMATELY 30-45 MINUTES WHILE REEDER WORKED ON THE CAR.

UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CTS T.M. ROBINSON RECEIVED A CALL AT HIS RESIDENCE FROM DEPUTY HEBERT OF THE ASCENSION PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE.  HERBERT ADVISED THAT A LOCAL CITIZEN HAD REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR IN THE UPRR YARD AT DONALDSONVILLE, LOUISIANA.   A SHERRIF'S PATROL UNIT CONFIRMED THIS, RELATING THAT A LOUD WHISTLING NOISE, AUDIBLE FROM SEVERAL HUNDRED YARDS AWAY, WAS COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR CHVX 291502, LOADED WITH STYRENE.  DEPUTY HERBERT ADDED THE CHEVRON CHEMICAL HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND WERE RESPONDING TO THE SCENE.  THE ASCENSION PARISH HAZ/MAT TEAM WAS ON THE SCENE AND HAD REQUESTED THAT ROBINSON RESPOND. ROBINSON PROCEEDED TO THE SCENE AND WHILE IN ROUTE TELEPHONED UPRR MTO AT ADDIS, BOB LENZER. LENZER WAS INFORMED OF THE POTENTIAL PROBLEM AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THE UPRR HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER.  ROBINSON THEN TELEPHONED UPRR DIRECTOR-CTS, MR. L. R. TIERNEY.  TIERNEY RESPONDED TO THE HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER WHERE HE CONTACTED UPRR DIRECTOR TRAIN MGMT, J.M. SEAGLE. UPON ARRIVAL AT DONALDSONVILLE ROBINSON WAS MET BY ASCENSION PAR. HAZ/MAT TEAM MEMBERS COUBURN HOOD AND DENNIS HUTCHINSON, DONALDVILLE FIRE CHIEF KIRK LANDRY AND CHEVRON RESPONSE TECHNICIANS DONAVAN STEIB AND LAMAR TRIPP.  TRIPP ADVISED THAT THE CAR WAS A "RESIDUE/EMPTY".  TRIPP AND STEIB HAD ALREADY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING NITROGEN GAS PAST THE MANWAY GASKET.  TRIPP EXPLAINED THAT DEXCO OFFLOADS THE CAR BY PUSHING IT WITH NITROGEN.  DEXCO HAD FAILED TO BLEED THE EXCESS PRESSURE. THIS PROBLEM HAD OCCURRED ON PREVIOUS OCCASIONS, BUT TRIPP THOUGHT THAT IT HAD BEEN RESOLVED.  ROBINSON TELEPHONED TIERNEY AND SEAGLE.  TIERNEY ADVISED THAT THEY HAD JUST SPOKEN TO CHEVRON REPRESENTATIVES AND HAD RECEIVED THE SAME INFORMATION.  ROBINSON ACCOMPAINED TRIPP AND STEIB BACK TO THE CAR WHERE TRIPP WAS ABLE TO FURTHER TIGHTEN THE MANWAY BOLTS.  THIS REDUCED THE LEAK TO AN IN-AUDIBLE CONDITION.  THEN THE AIR INLET VALVE WAS OPENED TO RELIEVE THE EXCESS PRESSURE.  AFTER ABOUT 80 MINUETES THE CAR WAS SECURED AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED.  ON MONDAY, 2/7/94, ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MR. DEAN SMITH, REGULATORY  COMPLIANCE  MANAGER FOR DOW CHEMICAL AT PLAQUEMINE, LA. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT DEXCO IS A JOINT VENTURE OF DOW AND EXXON.  THE DEXCO FACILITY IS LOCATED WITH A DOW'S LOUISIANA DIVISION.  SMITH WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND RELATED THAT HE WOULD AGGRESSIVELY FOLLOW UP WITH PLANT PERSONNEL AND REPORT THIS ON TO THE PLANT MANAGER AS WELL.

column168: V11 & V111 ABOVE:NO PACKAGING FAILURE INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT. OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO A STATION'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  AFTER TAKING THE INITIAL STICK READINGS, THE DRIVER DETERMINED THAT THERE SHOULD BE OVER 200 GALLONS OF ROOM LEFT IN THE UNDERGROUND TANK AFTER DELIVERY.  JUST AS OUR CARGO TANK WAS ABOUT TO EMPTY OUT, THE UNDERGROUND TANK OVERFILLED AND DIESEL FUEL CAME OUT THE REMOTE CAP AND RAN ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  OUR DRIVER STOPPED THE DELIVERY AND APPLIED CLAY ABSORBANTS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL ON THE PARKING LOT.  NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.  A CLEANUP CREW FROM LUZON ENVIRONMENTAL CO. WAS CALLED IN TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP AND TO PROVIDE PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE NEW JERSEY DEPT.  OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION'S 24 HOUR EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS CALLED AND THEY ASSIGNED A CASE #94-2-4-1746-25 TO THIS INCIDENT.  SPILL CAUSE WAS EITHER AN INACCURATE INITIAL STICK READING OR THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK IS NOT LEVEL.

column168: DRIVERS REPORT ON CAUSTIC SPILL.  I DOUG POTTER DRIVER FOR D.M.S.S. TRANSPORATION INC.  LEASED TO CALEDONIA LINES WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF CAUSTIC SODA TO EMPIRE CHEESE IN CUBA, NY ON FEB. 15TH, 1994.  ONXYS B/L #25-62279-00 JONES B/L #08755.  WHEN UNLOADING AT EMPIRE CHEESE YOU HAVE TO BACK INTO A INSIDE BAY WHERE THE MILK TRUCKS UNLOAD, SO BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ARE INSIDE, AND THE HOOK UPS FOR UNLOADING ARE ON THE WALL BEHIND THE TRAILER.  ALL THE EQUIPMENT THEY USE TO UNLOAD MILK TRUCKS IS BEHIND THE TRAILER.  THE TANK THAT THE CAUSTIC GOES INTO IS ABOUT 30 FEET TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, AND TO GET TO IT YOU HAVE TO WALK THROUGH A SMALL BREAKROOM AT THE BACK OF THE BREAKROOM IS A DOOR TO THE TANK ROOM, JUST ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THE DOOR IS THE CAUSTIC TANK.  THERE IS ONLY ONE WAY IN AND OUT OF THIS AREA, AND THATS THRU THE BREAKROOM AND THE ONLY WAY OUT OF THE BREAKROOM IS THE DOOR THATS ABOUT 12 FEET BEHIND THE REAR OF TRAILER.  WHILE UNLOADING YOU HAVE TO WALK BACK EVERY SO OFTEN AND CHECK THE LEVEL OF THE TANK, BECAUSE THE TANK ONLY HOLDS ABOUT 3600 GALLONS, AND YOU HAVE TO BE CAREFUL NOT TO OVERFLOW THE TANK.  I HAD UNLOADED ABOUT HALF OF THE LOAD, I HAD GONE BACK TO CHECK THE LEVEL OF THE TANK ON MY WAY BACK OUT TO THE TRAILER THE HOSE SPLIT OPEN ABOUT 3 INCHES BEHIND THE TRAILER HOOK UP.  THE SPLIT WAS ACROSS THE TOP OF HOSE, AND CAUSTIC WAS SPRAYING OUT IN A STREAM ONTO THE BREAKROOM DOOR.  I HAD NO WAY OUT OF THIS ROOM TO SHUT THE TRAILER VALVE WITHOUT GOING THRU THIS SPRAY.  A PLANT WORKER WAS OUT BY THE TRAILER BUT HE COULD DO NOTHING BECAUSE HE DID'NT HAVE ANY PROTECTIVE GEAR ON.  I HAD ALL MY GEAR ON, BUT DID'NT WANT TO TRY TO RUN THRU THE SPRAY OF CAUSTIC.  I KNEW I HAD TO BECAUSE I WAS THE ONLY ONE IN PROTECTIVE GEAR, AND I HAD TO GET THE SPILL STOPPED, SO I MADE SURE ALL MY GEAR WAS CLOSED UP AS TIGHT AS POSSIBLE, AND OPENED THE DOOR AND STARTED TO RUN THRU THE SPRAY.  ABOUT HALF WAY TO THE TRAILER I SLIPPED IN THE CAUSTIC ON THE FLOOR AND FELL DOWN.  WHEN I FELL MY HARDHAT AND FACE SHEILD CAME OFF.  CAUSTIC RAN ALL OVER THE LEFT SIDE OF MY HEAD. WHEN THIS HAPPENED.  I GOT BACK UP AS QUICK AS I COULD GET TO THE TANK AND CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE STOPPING THE FLOW.  THE TIME IT TOOK TO SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER AFTER THE HOSE SPLIT WAS ABOUT 30 TO 45 SECONDS, AND ABOUT 20 TO 25 GALLONS HAD SPILLED.  AFTER CLOSING THE VALVE THERE WAS A WATER HOSE ON THE FLOOR BY THE REAR OF THE TRAILER I TOOK IT AND STARTED SPRAYING MY FACE AND HEAD DOWN TRYING TO WASH OFF THE CAUSTIC.  IT WAS A FEW SECONDS AND THE PLANT WORKER CAME OVER AND STARTED SPRAYING ME DOWN WITH THE WATER HOSE.  I TOOK OFF MY RAIN COAT-RUBBER GLOVES-SAFETY GLASSED-GOGGLES AND LET THEM WASH ME DOWN AFTER A WHILE THIS THEY STOPPED AND SENT ME TO CUBA HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT.  ONE OF THE PLANT WORKERS TOOK ME THERE.  AT THE HOSPITAL THEY WASHED THE EXPOSED AREAS DOWN SOME MORE CHECKED ME FOR BURNS AND LET ME GO.  I ONLY HAD SLIGHT BURNS AROUND MY LEFT EAR ON MY NECK

column168: ON 02/24/94 AT APPROXIMATELY 0143 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT OF PAINT THAT WAS LEAKING ON OUR HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY THOMAS BRECKEL/SORTER.  MR. BRECKEL WAS SORTING FREIGHT WHEN HE LIFTED A STEEL DRUM AND EXPERIENCE A BAD STINGING SENSATION IN A LACERATION ALREADY PRESENT ON HIS HAND.  WHEN HE LOOKED AT HIS HAND, HE SAW THAT THE SHIPMENT HE WAS LIFTING WAS LEAKING AND THE PRODUCT HAD ENTERED THE LACERATION.  BRECKEL IMMEDIATELY WENT TO THE NEAREST WASH FACILITY (WITHIN 30 YARDS) AND WASHED HIS HANDS THROUGHLY FOR APPROXIMATELY 15 MINUTES.  THE SHIPMENT WAS INVESTIGATED BY ME AND MY SPILL TEAM PARTNER (JACKIE LOVE/HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN).  WE DONNED NIOSH APPROVED CARTIDGE TYPE RESPIRATORS AND LATEX GLOVES.  WE FOUND THE SHIPMENT OF PAINT.  A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS ATTACHED TO THE SHIPMENT.  THE SPIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A UN LAL STEEL DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ. OF PRODUCT AT THE BUNG. NO INDICATION OF DEFECTIVE PACKAGE INTEGRITY WAS VISIBLE UPON OUR INVESTIGATION.  MISS LOVE AND I REPACKAGED THE SHIPMENT IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.  A 5800.1 FORM WAS COMPLETED.  WITHIN 20 MINUTES AFTER THE AREA WAS CLEARED AND MR. BRECKEL RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA, HE BECAME FAINT AND ACTUALLY LOST CONSCIENCENESS. HE GOT BACK ON HIS FEET AND CAME INTO THE OFFICE TO ADVISE HIS MANAGER (JAMES CURTIS) WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED ME AND OUR ON BASE EMERGENCY MEDICAL TECHNICIANS.  MR. BRECKEL'S CONDITION RAPIDLY DECLINED AND THE LOCAL EMS UNIT WAS CONTACTED TO TRANSPORT HIM TO EMERGENCY MEDICAL CARE.  PLEASE REFERENCE ACCIDENT REPORT. A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND SHIPPERS DECLARATION (WHICH IS ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS REPORT) ACCOMPANIED MR. BRECKEL TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM.  THE SHIPMENT HAS BEEN HELD IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY STORAGE AREA PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 HRS, MONDAY, 02/21/94, BOB HOPKINS, ASSIST TERMINAL MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE, WA. NOTIFIED SAHM VERN LIBBY THAT TWO MITSUI CONTAINERS, MOLU 287305 AND MOLU 291875 HAD BEEN UNLOADED AND RELEASED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  HOWEVER, AT TIME OF ARRIVAL, PORT OF SEATTLE, TERMINAL 30, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE PORT OF SEATTLE DIVERTED THE CONTAINERS TO TERMINAL 106 WEST, SEATTLE, WA. PENDING DISPOSITION. INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED BOTH THE ABOVE LISTED CONTAINERS ARRIVED SEATTLE LOADED IN THE WELL OF DTTX 56745, WHICH WAS THE 2ND NORTH CAR IN TRACK 3, SEATTLE YARD. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED RESIDUE ON THE WELL FLOOR, INDICATING BOTH CONTAINERS HAD BEEN LEAKING WHILE LOADED.  DTTX 56745 WAS ISOLATED PENDING DECONTAMINATION. AT TIME OF SAHM LIBBY'S ARRIVAL, THE SEATTLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WERE ON SITE.  ALSO, MR. MEL FRANK, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, HIRED BY KATHY GORDON, MITSUI ACCESSING THE LEAKING CONTAINERS. IT WAS DECIDED THAT BOTH CONTAINERS BE ISOLATED FOR THE NIGHT, WITH CLEANUP TO START IN THE AM 02/22. CLEANUP STARTED WITH THE CONTAMINATION OF DTTX 56745 WITH THE STACK CAR BEING RELEASED AT 1110HRS. ON 2/22. IT WAS NOTED THAT BOTH CONTAINERS WERE LOADED WITH 76-55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, LABLED CORROSIVE LIQUID, PROTECTED BY 4-2X4'S HORIZONTALLY AND 4-2X4'S VERTICALLY AT THE REAR. ALSO, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE LOADED 2 DRUMS TO TIP AND RUB THE ROLLING HOOPS AND CHIMES. FURTHER, THERE WAS AN APPROXIMATE 2'GAP BETWEEN THE 2X4'S IN THE REAR OF CONTAINER MOLU 287305. UNABLE TO PROVIDE INFORMATION REFERENCE CONTAINER MOLU 291875 BECAUSE THE 2X4 BLOCKING HAD BEEN REMOVED PRIOR TO SAHM LIBBY'S ARRIVAL.  MOLU 287305 HAD 1 - 55 GALLON DRUM ON THE BOTTOM, IN THE NOSE LEAKING AS THE RESULT OF THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP BEING RUBBED AND ABRADED, ACCOUNT THERE WAS NO SEPARATION BETWEEN DRUMS.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPAC DRUM AND SECURED. MOLU 291875 HAD TWO DRUMS LOADED ON THE REAR TOP TIER TILTED, ALLOWING THE TOP CHIME OF ONE DRUM TO RUB UNDER THE TOP CHIME OF ANOTHER DRUM UNTIL THE DRUM BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE BUNG LOADED WITHIN THE CONTAINER ALSO, ONE OF THE FIVE LEAKING DRUMS IN CONTAINER MOLU 291875 WAS ACCIDENTLY STRUCK WITH A FORKLIFT WHILE BEING UNLOADED BY FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL'S FORCES.  ALL FIVE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPAC DRUMS AND SECURED ON 2/24. FINAL DISPOSITION OF WHETHER CONTENTS OF BOTH CONTAINERS WOULD BE REJECTED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR THEIR HANDLING OR WHETHER PORTIONS OF BOTH CONTAINERS WOULD BE FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION WAS PENDING AT THE TIME REPORT WAS WRITTEN.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2000 HRS, MONDAY, 02/21/94, BOB HOPKINS, ASSIST TERMINAL MANAGER, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT, SEATTLE, WA. NOTIFIED SAHM VERN LIBBY THAT TWO MITSUI CONTAINERS, MOLU 287305 AND MOLU 291875 HAD BEEN UNLOADED AND RELEASED WITHOUT INCIDENT.  HOWEVER, AT TIME OF ARRIVAL, PORT OF SEATTLE, TERMINAL 30, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING. THE PORT OF SEATTLE DIVERTED THE CONTAINERS TO TERMINAL 106 WEST, SEATTLE, WA. PENDING DISPOSITION. INVESTIGATION DEVELOPED BOTH THE ABOVE LISTED CONTAINERS ARRIVED SEATTLE LOADED IN THE WELL OF DTTX 56745, WHICH WAS THE 2ND NORTH CAR IN TRACK 3, SEATTLE YARD. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED RESIDUE ON THE WELL FLOOR, INDICATING BOTH CONTAINERS HAD BEEN LEAKING WHILE LOADED.  DTTX 56745 WAS ISOLATED PENDING DECONTAMINATION. AT TIME OF SAHM LIBBY'S ARRIVAL, THE SEATTLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM WERE ON SITE.  ALSO, MR. MEL FRANK, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, HIRED BY KATHY GORDON, MITSUI ACCESSING THE LEAKING CONTAINERS. IT WAS DECIDED THAT BOTH CONTAINERS BE ISOLATED FOR THE NIGHT, WITH CLEANUP TO START IN THE AM 02/22. CLEANUP STARTED WITH THE CONTAMINATION OF DTTX 56745 WITH THE STACK CAR BEING RELEASED AT 1110HRS. ON 2/22. IT WAS NOTED THAT BOTH CONTAINERS WERE LOADED WITH 76-55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, LABLED CORROSIVE LIQUID, PROTECTED BY 4-2X4'S HORIZONTALLY AND 4-2X4'S VERTICALLY AT THE REAR. ALSO, BOTH CONTAINERS WERE LOADED 2 DRUMS TO TIP AND RUB THE ROLLING HOOPS AND CHIMES. FURTHER, THERE WAS AN APPROXIMATE 2'GAP BETWEEN THE 2X4'S IN THE REAR OF CONTAINER MOLU 287305. UNABLE TO PROVIDE INFORMATION REFERENCE CONTAINER MOLU 291875 BECAUSE THE 2X4 BLOCKING HAD BEEN REMOVED PRIOR TO SAHM LIBBY'S ARRIVAL.  MOLU 287305 HAD 1 - 55 GALLON DRUM ON THE BOTTOM, IN THE NOSE LEAKING AS THE RESULT OF THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP BEING RUBBED AND ABRADED, ACCOUNT THERE WAS NO SEPARATION BETWEEN DRUMS.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPAC DRUM AND SECURED. MOLU 291875 HAD TWO DRUMS LOADED ON THE REAR TOP TIER TILTED, ALLOWING THE TOP CHIME OF ONE DRUM TO RUB UNDER THE TOP CHIME OF ANOTHER DRUM UNTIL THE DRUM BEGAN LEAKING FROM THE BUNG LOADED WITHIN THE CONTAINER ALSO, ONE OF THE FIVE LEAKING DRUMS IN CONTAINER MOLU 291875 WAS ACCIDENTLY STRUCK WITH A FORKLIFT WHILE BEING UNLOADED BY FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL'S FORCES.  ALL FIVE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPAC DRUMS AND SECURED ON 2/24. FINAL DISPOSITION OF WHETHER CONTENTS OF BOTH CONTAINERS WOULD BE REJECTED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR THEIR HANDLING OR WHETHER PORTIONS OF BOTH CONTAINERS WOULD BE FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION WAS PENDING AT THE TIME REPORT WAS WRITTEN.

HILL, WHO ADVISED TO MOVE CAR INTO NORTH LITTLE ROCK TERMINAL. HILL'S INSPECTION REVEALED LIQUID ARGON DRIPPING FROM GROUND LEVEL CABINET ON LEFT SIDE OF CAR. MANAGER HILL REMOVE SEALS M.P.R.R. 20-14742 & 43 TO GAIN ACCESS, FOUND TWO INCH PRESSURE CAP OFF AND LAYING IN CABINET ALLOWING LIQUID TO RUN FROM TWO INCH PIPE. SECURED TWO INCH PRESSURE CAP WHICH SECURED LEAK. CONTACTED CHEMTREC'S JOE MILLAZZO WHO ASSIGNED #27010 TO THIS INCIDENT. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE SAM HAYMAS WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED A PAGE FROM GARY HUNTER, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, ADVISING TANK CAR MKT 100417 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE SCYR-15 AT 1955 HOURS, FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 18, 1994. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE NEOPRENE GASKET ON THE COVER PLATE WAS DETERIORATED AND DISTORTED, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. AS A LIKE TYPE GASKET WAS NOT AVAILABLE, A FIBER GASKET AND GOR-TEX WAS USED TO REPLACE THE DEFECTIVE GASKET. THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS THEN SECURED. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE AND IN GOOD ORDER. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, OR TO THE COUNTY OF SAN BERNARDION DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH SERVICES.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA. THAT TANK CAR GATX 57789 WAS NOTED LEAKING WHILE BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS. THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED, HOWEVER, THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE CAR. THE CAR WAS SET TO THE WEST END OF YARD TRACK #202 (RD2) AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. THIS CAR ARRIVED YERMO IN THE CNYR-15 AT 0830 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 15, 1994, AFTER BEING RECEIVED FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC ON INTERCHANGE AT COLTON, CALIFORNIA. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED THE CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. (5) OF THE (6) SWING BOLTS USED TO SECURE THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND. THE REMAINING BOLT WAS LOOSENED IN ORDER TO INSPECT THE GASKET MATERIAL, WHICH APPEARED TO BE INTACT AND IN GOOD CONDITION. THE COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE THEN PROPERLY SECURED, WHICH CURTAILED THE VAPOR BEING EMITTED FROM THE LADING. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE AND IN GOOD ORDER. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

AT 1445 HOURS, TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 15, 1994, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D. A. LOW WAS CONTACTED BY TERRY DOYLE, FRA, THAT TANK CAR ADMX 29536, HAD A HIZZING NOISE COMING FROM VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. TANK CAR WAS LOCATED AT COMMERCE CITY YARDS, WHICH IS LOCATED ONE QUARTER OF A MILE FROM CONOCO'S DENVER PLANT. AT TIME OF CALL MANAGER D. A. LOW WAS AT LOOKOUT, WYOMING, TRANSFERRING FUEL FROM DAMAGED UNITS. CONOCO WAS CONTACTED AND HAD TANK CAR SWITCH TO THEIR PLANT WHERE TANK CAR WAS OFF-LOADED AND REPAIRED. LARRY MC VAY, ALCOHOL SUPERINTENDENT, ADM, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.

DURING A ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, REEDER HEARD THE SOUND OF ESCAPING GAS FROM THIS CAR. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT GAS WAS COMING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE. A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID WAS IN THE VALVE AND WAS BUBBLING. GAS WAS ALSO ESCAPING FROM AROUND THE PACKING GLAND ON THE AIR LINE. THE VALVE HANDLE WAS LOOSE AND COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED DUE TO BAD THREADS ON THE STEM. WHEN THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION, THE HOUSING COULD NOT BE CLOSED. LIQUID COULD BE SEEN AROUND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG THOUGH IT WAS TIGHT. THE CAR WAS SECURED AND MOVED WITHOUT DELAY. CHEMTREC REPORT #26932 COVERS THIS RELEASE.

DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTION, REEDER DISCOVERED A STAIN AROUND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE AIR LINE PLUG WAS LOOSE. LIQUID AND A STAIN WAS VISIBLE AROUND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG  THOUGH IT WAS TIGHT. THE AIR LINE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR RELEASED WITHOUT DELAY. DUPONT CANADA AND DUPONT HOUSTON WERE CONTACTED ABOUT THE PROBLEM. CHEMTREC REPORT #26932 COVERS THIS INCIDENT.

MANAGER CTS LERCH NOTED THE SIDES AND AREA AROUND THE SAFETY VENT TO BE MOIST ON LOADED TANK CAR KCCX 2493 CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, CORROSIVE, UN1830; LOCATED ON EAST DEPARTURE TRACK 6. INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY VENT BY MGR LERCH REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISK TO BE RUPTURED. RUPTURED BS&B #100 DISK WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW BS&B #100 DISK WHICH SECURED THE CAR. NOTIFICATIONS; 1540HRS, 2-14-94, CHEM-TREC, JEFF BOTWINICK, #26902; 1550HRS, NEBRASKA D.E.Q., KIRK MORROW, #021494-KM-1550; 1555HRS, U.P.R.R. E.M.G., MGR. STEVE MCNAUGHTON, 1600HRS, U.P.R.R  M.D.I. STAN KINSTLEY; 1215HRS, 2-15-94, KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER, MGR. TRANSPORTATION, STAN ANDERSON.

TANK CAR WAS OBSERVED BY UPRR PERSONNEL AT ALEXANDRIA, LOUISIANA LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER. THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITHOUT INCIDENT. UPON NOTIFICATION, UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER-CTS, T. M. ROBINSON RESPONDED FROM BATON ROUGE, LA. INSPECTION BY ROBINSON REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS TOO LARGE. ALTHOUGH THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHT, THE GASKET COULD NOT FORM A SEAL BETWEEN THE NOZZLE AND THE COVER PLATE. ROBINSON REMOVED SEAL "CHEVRON 003201" FROM A MANWAY BOLT, REMOVED THE IMPROPER SIZED MANWAY GASKET AND INSTALLED A GASKET OF THE PROPER SIZE. THE MANWAY WAS RESECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED BY CHEMTREC COMMUNICATOR BILL GASSON. ADDITIONALLY, ROBINSON NOTIFIED TROOPER BOUDREAUX ON THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZ/MAT HOTLINE.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED THAT A LOAD OF BENZENE HAD DERAILED IN BIG SPRING YARD, WAS ON ITS SIDE AT A 65 DEGREE ANGLE, AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY AT A RATE OF 1 DROP PER MINUTE. MTO KEITH NORRIS WAS AT THE SCENE AND PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK. HE HAD A CALICHE BERM PLACED AROUND THE CAR AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE BECAUSE OF A CREEK LOCATED 40 FEET FROM THE CAR. UPRR HARRIMAN DISPATCH CONTACTED CHEMTREC, WHO IN TURN CONTACTED FINA REPRESENTATIVE ALLEN BROWN (409-963-6806). MR. BROWN DISPATCHED FINA'S SAFETY/EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE BIG SPRING REFINERY, JIM WOOD AND BILL SWAFFORD. THEY RESPONDED TO SCENE, TIGHTENED THE MANWAY AND STOPPED THE LEAK. MR. WOOD ADVISED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS NOT BENZENE. IT WAS COSDENOL-104 WHICH WAS PROMARILY XYLENE, OFTEN USED TO BLEND WITH GASOLINE. HULCHER SERVICES STARTED RERAILING OPERATIONS AT 0020 HRS., 2-17-94. A TRENCH WAS MADE TO ACCOMMODATE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE CAR WAS SUCCESSFULLY UPRIGHTED AND RERAILED AT 0320 HRS. UPRR MMM JAMES PIERCE STATED THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFER BECAUSE OF EXTENSIVE MECHANICAL DAMAGE. FINA WAS ADVISED OF THE CAR STATUS AND SUPPLIED TANK CAR GATX 28296 FOR THE TRANSFER. REGIONAL CTS MANAGER BOB STINE WAS ADVISED AND SET TRANSFER FOR MONDAY, 2-21-94.

MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) S. COVI WAS NOTIFIED BY P. NEILSON OF SILVERBOW, MT, THAT TRAIN SBPC 25 HAD DERAILED AT MAIDEN ROCK AND THAT TANK CAR GATX 13408 HAD OVER TURNED AND WAS LEAKING. MCTS COVI RESPONDED AND UPON ARRIVAL NOTED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ROD. PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE PACKING GLAND AREA OF THE ROD AT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON PER 30 MINUTES. TIGHTENING OF THE ROD DID NOT STOP LEAK SO STEEL PUTTY AND RADIATOR HOSE/CLAMPS WERE APPLIED WHICH SLOWED AND CONTAINED LEAK UNTIL CAR WAS UPRIGHTED. CAR WAS RERAILED AND SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR GATX 17003 IN POCATELLO, ID. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED FOR FINAL DISPOSAL AT ECDC, SALT LAKE CITY, UT. JIM COOPER OF CHEMTREC, MIKE HANNOCK OF FLYING J AND DAN DENNEHY OF MONTANA HEALTH DEPARTMENT WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED A PAGE FROM MARTIN VASQUEZ, SUPERVISOR YARD OPERATIONS, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LOCAL INDUSTRY WITH A LEAKING TANK CAR. DEVELOPED THAT CLOROX (INDUSTRY TRACK 10-723) HAD FIVE TANK CARS ON THEIR DOCK TRACK, AND ONE OF THEIR PLANT PERSONNEL NOTICED A CHLORINE ODOR BEING EMITTED FROM ONE OF THE TANK CARS. THE PLANT PERSONNEL APPLIED A CAP FROM A CHLORINE "C" KIT OVER THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WHICH CURTAILED THE LEAK. CLORLOX REQUESTED THE TANK CAR BE SWITCHED FROM THE DOCK TRACK TO THEIR TANK CAR UNLOADING RACK, WHICH IS SITUATED INSIDE A SECURE ENCLOSURE, IN ORDER TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS.

column42: ETHYL METHYL KETONE OR METHYL ETHYL KETONE
column168: AN UNMARKED PACKAGED LEAKED, WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN FLAMMABLE LIQUD LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CAP.  WAS CLEANED UP ACCORDING TO DMP PROGRAM. REMAINDER RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

ON OUR LOAD MANIFEST WE PUT PALLET 9526 IN P1.  THE CREW BEGAN COMPLAINING ABOUT AN UNBEARABLE ODOR ON THE AIRCRAFT.  WE COULD NOT LOCATE THE EXACT CAUSE BUT WE DID NARROW IT DOWN TO THIS PALLET.  SINCE WE COULD NOT PIN POINT THE PIECE OF FRT CAUSING THE ODOR WE BUMPED THE CONTAINER AND GOT THE PLANE OUT.      ONCE ON OUR DOCK WE BROKE DOWN THE PALLET AND DISCOVERED A WOOD CRATE THAT WAS WET AND SMELLED. CONTACTED THE HUB AND OPEN THE CRATE TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS CAUSING THE ODOR BECAUSE WE COULD NOT "ASSUME" THE CAUSE TO BE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SINCE THERE WAS NO D/G LABELS OR DECLARATION.    WHEN OPENED, WE FOUND 1 PROPANE LAMP WITH A REPLACEMENT PROPANE CARTRIDGE, A BURNER THAT WAS APPPROX HALF FULL OF FUEL AND AN ANTIQUE OIL LAMP WITH FUEL IN IT ALSO.    THE SECOND CRATE WE LOCATED WE ALSO OPENED JUST IN CASE AND DISCOVERED A FLOOR HEATER WITH SOME LIQUID FUEL IN IT.  WE HAVE PUT ALL THE IMPLEMENTS WITH FUEL IN OUR SALVAGE DRUM. AFTERWARDS, IN A CONVERSATION WITH THE LEAD GROUND HANDLERS HE SAID ONE OF HIS PEOPLE COMMENTED THEY SMELLED SOMETHING IMMEDIATELY UPON OPENING THE MAIN CARGO DOOR.  THE PLANE SIDE REP INFORMED ME ONE OF THE CREW MEMBERS SAID THEY WERE ABLE TO SMELL SOMETHING ALL THERE WAS FROM ICT.  THIS EVEN THOUGH THE FRT WAS IN P11 ON THAT LEG OF THE TRIP.  IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS PLZ CONTACT ROSS TROUTNER/MCI HE CAN CONTACT WITH ANY QUESTIONS.
